# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: siege
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Over the course of 47 hours from January 19 to January 21, 1973, four robbers in Brooklyn, New York City, took hostages and engaged in a standoff with the New York City Police Department (NYPD).
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] One police officer was killed, and two officers and a perpetrator were injured, all within the first three hours of the incident; there were no further casualties during the standoff.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The incident began on the morning of January 19, when Shulab Abdur Raheem (24), Dawd A.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Rahman (22), Yusef Abdallah Almussadig (23), and Salih Ali Abdullah (26) robbed the John and Al's sporting goods store to acquire weapons for self-defense.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The four African American Sunni Muslim men were spurred by the 1973 Hanafi Muslim massacre in Washington, D.C. a day prior.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] NYPD officers responding to the robbery confronted them, sparking a shootout followed by a lengthy standoff when the perpetrators retreated back into the store and took twelve hostages.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The NYPD used crisis negotiation techniques pioneered by detective and psychologist Harvey Schlossberg to peacefully ensure the release and rescue of all twelve hostages and the surrender and arrest of all four perpetrators.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The incident, one of the longest standoffs in the NYPD's history, led to a shift in the standoff tactics of the NYPD and American law enforcement, who had previously believed standoffs were best resolved using lethal shock and awe attacks.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] It also highlighted the need for proper crisis negotiation and de-escalation in policing, and cemented Schlossberg as a "father of modern police psychology" as the NYPD and other agencies sought to learn from the events of the standoff.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The incident has since been described in retrospect as the "birthplace of hostage negotiation".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] John and Al's Sports, Inc. was a sporting goods store at 927 Broadway, straddling the border of the Bushwick and Bedford–Stuyvesant neighborhoods of Brooklyn.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The store opened in the 1930s and had been the victim of robberies "at least once every three months".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Its founder, Speilberger, was killed during one such robbery in 1967.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] By 1973, the store's owners were Samuel Rosenblum and Jerry Riccio, employees of Speilberger who took over after his death.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Harvey Schlossberg had recently been promoted from traffic officer to the NYPD's head psychologist after Police Commissioner Patrick V.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Murphy learned he had a doctorate in clinical psychology.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At the time, the NYPD did not have a fixed protocol for hostage situations, but recent incidents such as the 1971 Attica Prison riot and 1972 Munich massacre made developing one more of a pressing concern.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Schlossberg had disdain for contemporary police attitudes on hostage rescue, which centered around close-quarters combat and deadly force with more emphasis on defeating the hostage-takers than saving the hostages, as "cops refused to negotiate with killers".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Schlossberg promoted a more introspective approach, believing that forming a bond with the hostage-takers, analyzing their psyche, attempting to find solutions to their problems, and focusing on rescuing the hostages could lead to a peaceful resolution.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] He also believed in using patience and delays to draw out the standoff, which "allowed more time for the criminals to make mistakes and, just as crucially, to develop a rapport with their victims, leaving the hostage-takers less likely to harm them".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] A day prior to the incident, on January 18, seven Hanafi Sunni Muslims were murdered by the Black Mafia in Washington, D.C. after Hamaas Abdul Khaalis, an associate of Malcolm X and a family member of the victims, voiced strong opposition to the Nation of Islam.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] On Friday, January 19, 1973, at around 5:00 pm, Raheem, Rahman, Almussadig, and Abdullah entered John and Al's and began browsing the store's merchandise.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] After a few minutes, they suddenly drew a sawed-off shotgun and three handguns, and demanded firearms and ammunition for self-defense.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Only referring to each other as "one", "two", "three", and "four", the perpetrators armed themselves with additional weapons from the store, including rifles.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The NYPD's 90th Precinct was alerted to the robbery around 5:30 pm by the store's silent alarm and a student from Bushwick High School who managed to escape.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] When the first responding officers arrived at 5:42 pm, the perpetrators exited the store on Melrose Street using owner Rosenblum as a human shield and exchanged fire with them.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] It is unclear who fired first, but during the exchange Officer Jose Adorno was struck in the arm and Almussadig was struck in the abdomen, while Rosenblum managed to escape.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The perpetrators promptly retreated back into the store with twelve hostages.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] This sparked a shootout between them and police, prompting the activation and deployment of the NYPD's Emergency Service Unit (ESU).
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Officers shot out streetlights to provide more concealment, before power to the area was cut at an indeterminate point.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At around 6:10 pm, ESU Officer Stephen R.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Gilroy (29) was shot in the head and killed while taking a position behind an elevated railway pillar.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Officer Frank Carpentier was struck in his knee while moving his car to shield Gilroy's position in an attempt to rescue him or retrieve his body, and was rescued by an ESU team that laid suppressive fire on the perpetrators to cover their extraction.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] NYPD officers did not fire again for the rest of the standoff.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] By 7:05 pm, the NYPD had established a safe perimeter and a command post at 921 Broadway; up to six additional command posts would be established elsewhere along Broadway for various purposes.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The NYPD opted to use Schlossberg's crisis negotiation techniques to reason with the perpetrators and use patience to coerce them into peacefully releasing the hostages and surrendering.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] This was against the wishes of numerous police officers at the scene who sought retribution for Gilroy's death, as well as another NYPD psychologist who recommended an assault on the store using tear gas.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] After the perpetrators ripped out the store's phone lines, police used a megaphone to communicate with them, resulting in the release of a hostage around 8:00 pm.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] She told police the perpetrators would kill the hostages if they were not allowed to leave.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Around 9:00 pm, the perpetrators indicated they needed a doctor, but refused a request to surrender in exchange for medical treatment.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The NYPD deployed their Emergency Rescue Vehicle (ERV), an unarmed M113 armored personnel carrier nicknamed "Annie" or "The Tank", to rescue officers and civilians trapped along the streets and in stores across from John and Al's.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] During this operation, which lasted from approximately 9:00 pm to 11:00 pm, the perpetrators fired around 40 shots at the ERV to no effect.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Police noticed there was psychological value in the ERV's presence as the perpetrators "always got preoccupied with it", and used it for negotiations, positioned in close proximity to the storefront.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Other rescues of uninvolved bystanders were also conducted around the same time; for instance, an elevated train with its lights off was sent to extract stranded passengers at a nearby platform before the line was promptly shut down.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] However, residents of nearby apartments, as well as apparently people in some establishments, were ordered to remain inside until the standoff was resolved.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] This frustrated locals, some of whom attempted to leave anyway, including patrons of a pool hall who used a ladder to leave on their own after several hours of waiting.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Overnight, the hostages slept in sleeping bags, overseen by the perpetrators at gunpoint from a mezzanine in the store.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] On Saturday, January 20, at 12:50 am, another hostage was released, carrying a note urging Muslims to unite, as well as requests for food and medical attention.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At 4:00 am, Reverend Roy Brown of a Christian church in the area attempted to negotiate with the suspects from the ERV to no response.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Forty minutes later, another attempt was made by three imams.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] This time, the perpetrators allowed one imam to enter the store; he returned five minutes later and told police the perpetrators stated they were "willing to die for Allah".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] However, Schlossberg argued the perpetrators were merely bluffing, citing their requests for food and medical care as proof they wanted to live.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Attempts to communicate using the same imams at 9:25 am saw no response, prompting the NYPD to try using different individuals.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At 11:15 am, police gave the perpetrators a walkie-talkie to replace the megaphone they were given prior, but when Deputy Commissioner Benjamin Ward spoke through it, both the walkie-talkie and the megaphone were thrown out of the store.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At 2:45 pm, lawyers Sanford Katz and Gerald B.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Lefcourt offered to represent the perpetrators at trial, but were met by six shots at the ERV; when they urged the perpetrators to take the walkie-talkie and the ERV backed away, a hostage was sent out to retrieve it.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At 3:15 pm, the walkie-talkie was used to request sandwiches, cigarettes, and medical supplies; the sandwiches and cigarettes were approved, but the medical supplies were only promised once the perpetrators surrendered.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] News reports mention that relatives of the perpetrators were also sent to communicate with them, though it is unclear exactly when these occurred or whether the perpetrators responded.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Matthews, head of the National Economic Growth and Reconstruction Organization and Interfaith Hospital, arrived with a nurse, having been summoned by the NYPD.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] An offer was made for Matthews to treat Almussadig if he was brought out of the store, but the perpetrators made a counteroffer to release one hostage in exchange for Matthews and the nurse entering the store to treat Almussadig and serve as intermediaries.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] After "great consideration", the NYPD agreed, and the exchange was made.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Matthews and the nurse returned forty minutes later with the names and telephone numbers of the nine remaining hostages; around this time, the sandwiches and cigarettes requested by the perpetrators arrived and were placed outside the store.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Assaulting the store was deemed a "last resort" out of fears the perpetrators could be revered as martyrs.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Schlossberg told his superiors that if all else failed, they could simply let the perpetrators go in exchange for the hostages' safety, reasoning police could "always catch the criminals later", which Ward agreed with.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Letting the perpetrators leave was apparently seriously considered, to the point that the Port Authority Police Department had a car prepared to drive them to John F.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Kennedy International Airport so they could leave the United States.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] However, this was never offered to the perpetrators, and when one perpetrator briefly mentioned acquiring a travel visa during negotiations on January 21, Ward quickly changed the topic to ensure it would not be brought up again.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Around 8:00 pm, Matthews reentered the store with orange juice and medical supplies.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Forty minutes later, the nurse was sent in with a field telephone to replace the walkie-talkie, as its batteries were dying.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Matthews stated that Almussadig had a fever, and was potentially suffering from blood poisoning and an infection in his intestines, with a chance of death if he did not receive emergency treatment.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Reviewing the information from the perpetrators up to that point, Schlossberg deduced they "had not really formulated their own ideologies", and that their attempts at tying the robbery to vague political and religious causes were merely rationalization.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] On Sunday, January 21, the NYPD began moving to enclose the scene and break the siege.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] During the early morning, barbed wire was placed on Melrose Street to prevent attempts at fleeing, and the NYPD's Aviation Unit took aerial photographs of the store for planning.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Apparently sensing something, at 7:45 am, the perpetrators fired nine shots at a parked police car and stores across the street, and attempts to call them went unanswered.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] By 9:00 am, the "think tank" had proposed four entry methods: using explosives to breach the store, using a wrecking ball to the same effect, flooding the store with tear gas to incapacitate the perpetrators, or tunneling beneath the store to enter from below.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The ESU opted for the fourth approach and began moving drilling equipment to the basement of the furniture store next to John and Al's.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] By now, a massive crowd of spectators had formed at the perimeter, and news of the standoff had reached well across New York City.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] People stood on cars for a better view, to the point that *The Village Voice* writer Clark Whelton recalled seeing cars pressed to the ground from how many people were standing on them.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Some witnesses who sympathized with the perpetrators raised their fists in solidarity, while off-duty police officers and firefighters arrived to see what was happening, adding to the already tense atmosphere of the heavy police presence.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Rumors spread surrounding the incident, including that the perpetrators were members of the Black Liberation Army or that the police were waiting for an armored train to arrive on the elevated railway.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The crowd apparently viewed the standoff as little more than an entertaining spectacle, with some saying it was "better than the Super Bowl", and several people became increasingly frustrated with the inaction over time, throwing bottles and attempting to breach police lines.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Whelton summarized the general mood: "Half the people want the gunmen to come out fighting.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The other half want the cops to go in shooting.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Everybody wants blood." This frustrated the NYPD, especially Schlossberg, who feared the crowd and the media could negatively affect negotiations.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] At 12:45 pm, Riccio convinced the perpetrators to leave the hostages in a specific corner of the store where they would supposedly be out of the line of fire.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Unbeknownst to the perpetrators, in this corner was a half-inch plasterboard wall that hid a stairwell leading to the roof of the store.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] While the perpetrators went to investigate the sounds of the ESU moving the drilling equipment into the furniture store next door, the hostages broke through the wall and climbed the stairs to the roof.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] They were met by ESU officers who lowered a ladder from an adjoining roof, allowing all nine to escape.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The perpetrators attempted to reach the roof from another stairwell but were unable to, as they had barricaded it earlier.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] With the hostages now secure, the NYPD prepared for the possibility that the perpetrators would attempt a last stand as they had threatened to earlier.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Sporadic gunfire erupted from the store throughout the day to no effect.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Around 4:55 pm, after a brief prayer, Raheem, Rahman, and Abdullah, carrying Almussadig on a cot, exited the store and surrendered to police.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Raheem, Rahman, and Abdullah were apprehended and led away by waiting detectives, while Almussadig was taken to Kings County Hospital Center to treat his injuries.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In 1974, the trial of the four perpetrators was held at the New York Supreme Court in Brooklyn.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] It was also argued that Gilroy may have been killed by a ricocheting police bullet in a friendly fire mishap, not by deliberate fire from the perpetrators.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] On June 21, 1974, a jury consisting of ten white jurors and two black jurors, which was cautioned by the judge "not to be influenced by the defendants' 'religion, race or politics'", found the four defendants guilty of 41 counts, including assault, robbery, and kidnapping.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Raheem was convicted for Gilroy's murder.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In 1998, the New York State Division of Parole released Almussadig.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The public was not made aware he had been released until he died in 2003.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In 2008, Raheem expressed his regrets for the events of the incident, stating in a parole hearing, "I wish there was some way I could go back to the moment I decided to enter the store ...
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] I understand the pain I caused." In 2010, Raheem was released on parole from the Eastern Correctional Facility in Napanoch, New York.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] He is currently a social worker campaigning for restorative justice.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In October 2020, Abdullah died of a stroke he suffered at his 14th parole hearing, at 71 years old, after having served more than 40 years in prison.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In the immediate aftermath, the NYPD was somewhat divided on how the incident was handled.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Officers at the 90th Precinct, where Gilroy had been assigned, were angry that the perpetrators were apprehended alive, with one officer interviewed by *The New York Times* suggesting they should have used "hand grenades and bazookas" instead of negotiations after Gilroy was killed.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Gilroy's funeral was held at 9:30 am on January 23 at St.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Cecilia's Roman Catholic Church in Greenpoint, and he was buried at First Calvary Cemetery in Long Island City.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The NYPD's handling of the standoff was a turning point in American law enforcement's approach to hostage situations.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] Instead of brute force, police used psychology, firearm discipline, and patience to end the siege.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] These were techniques that were then codified in the NYPD's Hostage Negotiation Team and training program, both established later in 1973, using the tactics from the standoff as guiding principles.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] In retrospect, an NYPD captain described the incident as "the birthplace of hostage negotiation".
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] The 2022 documentary *Hold Your Fire* by Stefan Forbes recounts the events of the incident and highlights the NYPD's hostage negotiation strategies.
[src:siege/1973-brooklyn-hostage-crisis] As of 2022, the former site of John and Al's at 927 Broadway is Enrique's Unisex Salon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The **1982 Lebanon War**, also called the **Second Israeli invasion of Lebanon**, began on 6 June 1982, when Israel invaded southern Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The invasion followed a series of attacks and counter-attacks between the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) operating in southern Lebanon and the Israel Defense Forces (IDF), which had caused civilian casualties on both sides of the border.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli military operation, codenamed **Operation Peace for Galilee**, was launched after gunmen from the Abu Nidal Organization attempted to assassinate Shlomo Argov, Israel's ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli prime minister Menachem Begin blamed the PLO, using the incident as a *casus belli*.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was the second invasion of Lebanon by Israel, following the 1978 South Lebanon conflict.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis sought to end Palestinian attacks from Lebanon, destroy the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) in the country, and install a pro-Israel Maronite Christian government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces attacked and overran PLO positions in southern Lebanon and briefly clashed with the Syrian Army, who occupied most of the country's northeast.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli military, together with the South Lebanon Army, seized control of the southern half of Lebanon and laid siege to the capital Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Lebanese Forces however, despite their clandestine alliance with Israel, refused to participate in the war against the PLO as their leader Bachir Gemayel viewed any direct involvement as assisting an invading army.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Surrounded in West Beirut and subjected to heavy Israeli bombardment, the PLO and their allies negotiated a ceasefire with the aid of United States special envoy Philip Habib.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO, led by Yasser Arafat, were evacuated from Lebanon, overseen by a multinational peacekeeping force.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By expelling the PLO, removing Syrian influence over Lebanon, and installing a pro-Israeli Christian government led by President Bachir Gemayel, the Israeli government hoped to sign a treaty that would give Israel "forty years of peace".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the assassination of Gemayel in September 1982, Israel's position in Beirut became untenable and the signing of a peace treaty became increasingly unlikely.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] There was outrage at the IDF's role in the Israeli-backed, Phalangist-perpetrated Sabra and Shatila massacre of Palestinians and Lebanese Shias.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This stoked Israeli public disillusionment with the war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF withdrew from Beirut and ended its operation on 29 September 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The May 17 Agreement of 1983 ended the state of war between Israel and Lebanon, and provided for an Israeli withdrawal from the country.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Amid rising casualties from guerrilla attacks, the IDF retreated south of the Awali river on 3 September 1983.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From February to April 1985, the Israeli military undertook a phased withdrawal to its "South Lebanon security zone" along the border.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli occupation saw the emergence of Hezbollah, an Iranian-backed Shia Islamist group.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It waged a guerrilla war against the Israeli occupation until the IDF's final withdrawal from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In Israel, the 1982 invasion is also known as the **First Lebanon War**.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the 1948 Palestine war, 730,000 Palestinians fled or were forced to leave by Zionist forces, of whom 100,000 arrived in Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Most of the guerrillas would be recruited from Palestinian refugee camps.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1969, this population had grown to 235,000 as a result of natural population growth and immigration, including Palestinians who fled or were expelled by Israel during the 1967 war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On the eve of the 1982 Israeli invasion, the Palestinian population in Lebanon was 375,000.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The 1967 Six-Day War stimulated the growth of the Palestinian fedayeen (guerrillas).
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After 1967, the number of armed Palestinians increased from 200 to 2,000 and by 1968 it had reached 15,000.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Palestinian guerrilla action intended to serve as a war of national liberation for Palestinians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1968, PLO's objective was to establish a single democratic state in all of historical Palestine with equal rights for Jews, Muslims and Christians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was around this time that Palestinians began to conduct raids into Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1977, the objective had evolved to establishing a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, alongside Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1970, a large influx of Palestinians from Jordan went into Lebanon after the Black September conflict.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This caused an additional demographic imbalance within Lebanese society, and affected its democratic institutions established earlier by the National Pact.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 1975, the refugees numbered more than 300,000 and the PLO in effect created an unofficial state-within-a-state, particularly in Southern Lebanon, which then played an important role in the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] There had been continual violence near the Lebanon-Israel border between Israel and the PLO, starting from 1968; this increased following the relocation of PLO bases to Lebanon after the civil war in Jordan.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The violence between Israel and the PLO peaked during Operation Litani in 1978, provoked by the Coastal Road Massacre which was carried out by Palestinian militants.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As early as 1976, Israel had been assisting Lebanese Christian militias in their sporadic battles against the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During Operation Litani in 1978, Israel established a security zone in southern Lebanon with mostly Christian inhabitants, in which they began to supply training and arms to Christian militias which would later form the South Lebanese Army.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] But Israel's main partner was to be the Maronite Phalange party, whose paramilitary was led by Bashir Gemayel, a rising figure in Lebanese politics.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Gemayel's strategy during the early stages of the Lebanese Civil War was to provoke the Syrians into retaliatory attacks on Christians, such that Israel could not ignore.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In 1978, Menachem Begin declared that Israel would not allow a genocide of Lebanese Christians, while refusing direct intervention.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Hundreds of Lebanese militiamen began to train in Israel, at the IDF Staff and Command College.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From June to December 1980, the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) recorded an increase in activities along the border zone.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] No attacks by Palestinian forces on Israel were recorded, while the IDF incursions across the armistice line into Lebanon increased markedly, with minefields being laid, gun posts established, and generally involving numerous violations of Lebanese air-space and territorial waters.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This was formally protested by the Lebanese government to the UN Security Council and General Assembly in several communications as violations by Israel of United Nations Security Council Resolution 425.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the same period Israel protested numerous attacks by Palestinian forces, unrelated to the Lebanese border zone.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In his report for the period of 12 December 1980 to 12 June 1981 on UNIFIL activities, the Security Council Secretary General noted that infiltrations into the border zone by Palestinian armed forces had decreased relative to the previous six months.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Indeed, the PLO had recognized their vulnerable position, and avoided overtly provoking Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In contrast the IDF had launched various attacks on Lebanese territory often in support of the Lebanese Christian militia.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In doing so Israel had violated UN Security Council resolution 425 on hundreds of occasions [paragraph 58].
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Where the initiator(s) of attacks could be identified in the report, in 15 cases Palestinian militants were to blame while on 23 occasions the Militia and/or the IDF were the instigators, the latter also being responsible for the most violent confrontation of the period on 27 April [paragraph 52].
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From 16 June to 10 December 1981, a relative quiet was reported continuing from 29 May 1981 until 10 July.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This was broken when "Israeli aircraft resumed strikes against targets in southern Lebanon north of the UNIFIL area.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] (The Israeli strikes) led to exchanges of heavy firing between armed elements (Palestinians), on the one hand, and IDF and the de facto forces (Christian Militia) on the other.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 13 and 14 July, widespread Israeli air-strikes continued.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Armed elements (Palestinians) fired into the enclave and northern Israel." Israeli-initiated attacks had led to rocket and artillery fire on northern Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This pattern continued in the coming days.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel renewed its air strikes in an attempt to trigger a war that would allow it to drive out the PLO and restore peace to the region.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 17 July, the Israel Air Force launched a massive attack on PLO buildings in downtown Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] "Perhaps as many as three hundred died, and eight hundred were wounded, the great majority of them civilians." The Israeli army also heavily targeted PLO positions in south Lebanon without success in suppressing Palestinian rocket launchers and guns.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As a result, thousands of Israeli citizens who lived near the Lebanese border headed south.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 24 July 1981, United States Undersecretary of State Philip Habib brokered a ceasefire badly needed by both parties, the best achievable result from negotiations via intermediaries, aimed at complying with the decisions of UN Security Council resolution 490.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Between July 1981 and June 1982, as a result of the Habib ceasefire, the Lebanese-Israeli border "enjoyed a state of calm unprecedented since 1968." But the 'calm' was tense.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] US Secretary of State, Alexander Haig filed a report with US President Ronald Reagan on Saturday 30 January 1982 that revealed Secretary Haig's fear that Israel might, at the slightest provocation, start a war against Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Then, on 21 April 1982, after a landmine killed an Israeli officer while he was visiting a South Lebanese Army gun emplacement in Taibe, Lebanon, the Israeli Air Force attacked the Palestinian-controlled coastal town of Damour, killing 23 people.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fisk reports further on this incident: "The Israelis did not say what the soldier was doing ...
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] I discovered that he was visiting one of Haddad's artillery positions (Christian militia) and that the mine could have been lain [sic] as long ago as 1978, perhaps even by the Israelis themselves".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 9 May 1982, Israeli aircraft again attacked targets in Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Later that same day, UNIFIL observed the firing of rockets from Palestinian positions in the Tyre region into northern Israel, but none of the projectiles hit Israeli towns – the gunners had been ordered to miss.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Major-General Erskine (Ghana), Chief of Staff of UNTSO reported to the Secretary-General and the Security Council (S/14789, S/15194) that from August 1981 to May 1982, inclusive, there were 2096 violations of Lebanese airspace and 652 violations of Lebanese territorial waters.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The freedom of movement of UNIFIL personnel and UNTSO observers within the enclave remained restricted due to the actions of Amal and the South Lebanon Army under Major Saad Haddad's leadership with the backing of Israeli military forces.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Prior to establishing ceasefire in July 1981, U.N.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] I deeply deplore the extensive human suffering caused by these developments." The President of the U.N.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Security Council, Ide Oumarou of Niger, expressed "deep concern at the extent of the loss of life and the scale of the destruction caused by the deplorable events that have been taking place for several days in Lebanon".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From the ceasefire, established in July 1981, until the start of the war, the Israeli government reported 270 militant attacks by the PLO in Israel, the occupied territories, and the Jordanian and Lebanese border (in addition to 20 attacks on Israeli interests abroad).
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Arafat pressured the radical factions to maintain the ceasefire because he did not wish to provoke the Israelis into an all-out attack.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO acceptance of the ceasefire had led to dissension even within Fatah itself.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] A faction sympathetic to Abu Nidal forced a military confrontation, with accompanying arrests and executions — an event unprecedented in PLO internal disputes'.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Arafat even attempted to distance himself from Palestinian unrest on the West Bank to prevent an Israeli attack.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In contrast, Begin, Sharon and Eitan were searching for any excuse to neutralize their military opponents through a breach of the ceasefire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] They believed that Arafat was buying time to build up his conventional forces.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli interpretation of the conditions for the ceasefire placed responsibility for any act of Palestinian violence on Arafat's shoulders.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It presumed that Arafat had complete control, not only over all factions within the PLO such as the rejectionist Popular Front of George Habash, but also over those outside such as Abu Nidal's Fatah Revolutionary Council and Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front — General Command.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In Begin's eyes, the ceasefire was not geographically limited to the Lebanese border.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] He argued that if Palestinian terrorism struck internationally, then this too would be regarded as a breach of the ceasefire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Begin thus took a stand-off in a local battle as applying to the entire war anywhere in the Middle East or any incident internationally.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Eitan commented that there was no difference if a militant threw a grenade in Gaza or fired a shell at a Northern settlement — all such acts broke the ceasefire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Sharon similarly did not wish to draw distinctions between different Palestinian factions, since all blame had to be attached to the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] He dismissed attempts at more rational evaluation as masking the real issue.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In a speech to a Young Herut conference in April 1982, he accused those who tried to take a more objective standpoint of erecting 'a protective wall around the PLO inside and outside Israel'.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Further support comes from George Ball, that the PLO had observed the ceasefire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel, he said, continued looking for the "internationally recognized provocation" that Secretary of State Alexander Haig said would be necessary to obtain American support for an Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Secretary Haig's critics have accused him of "greenlighting" the Israeli Invasion of Lebanon in June 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Haig denies this and says he urged restraint.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The American reaction was that they would not apply any undue pressure on Israel to quit Lebanon as the Israeli presence in Lebanon may prove to be a catalyst for the disparate groups of Lebanon to make common cause against both Syrian and Israeli forces.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Haig's analysis, which Ronald Reagan agreed with, was that this uniting of Lebanese groups would allow President Elias Sarkis to reform the Lebanese central Government and give the Palestinian refugees Lebanese citizenship.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to Avi Shlaim, the real driving force behind the Israeli invasion to Lebanon was the defense minister Ariel Sharon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One of his aims was the destruction of PLO military infrastructure in Lebanon and undermining it as a political organization, in order to facilitate the absorption of the West Bank by Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The second aim was the establishment of the Maronite government in Lebanon, headed by Bashir Gemayel and signing the peace treaty between two countries, the third aim was the expelling of the Syrian Army from Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Also, according to Shlaim, with the completion of Israeli withdrawals from Sinai in March 1982, under the terms of the Egyptian-Israeli Peace Treaty, the Likud-led government of Israel hardened its attitude to the Arab world and became more aggressive.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The military plan with the code name "Big Pines", prepared by IDF, envisaged invasion to Lebanon up to the highway Damascus-Beirut and linking with Maronite forces.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was first presented to Israeli cabinet on 20 December 1981 by Begin, but rejected by the majority of ministers.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 3 June 1982 Israel's ambassador to the United Kingdom, Shlomo Argov was shot and seriously wounded in London by militants belonging to the Iraqi-backed Abu Nidal militant organization.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The attack was ordered by the Iraqi Intelligence Service.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the attack, the assassins drove to the Iraqi embassy in London, where they deposited the weapon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In his memoirs, Sharon stated that the attack was "merely the spark that lit the fuse".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli prime Minister Begin used this as the "internationally recognized provocation" necessary to invade Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The fact that the Abu Nidal organization was the longtime rival of PLO, that its head was condemned to death by the PLO court, and that the British police reported that PLO leaders were on the "hit list" of the attackers did not deter Begin.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the Israeli Cabinet meeting the following day, both Begin and Eitan belittled intelligence reports that the likely culprit was the Abu Nidal group.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Begin cut short his own advisor on terrorism, arguing that all Palestinian militants were members of the PLO, while Eitan ridiculed the intelligence staff for splitting hairs and demanded to strike at the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Yet Abu Nidal had broken with Arafat and PLO in 1974 over a fundamental principle: namely, that the Palestinian national movement would adopt a phased piecemeal approach to secure a Palestinian state and embark on a political path.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The lack of understanding of the difference between Palestinian groups and the total ignorance of Palestinian politics on the part an overwhelming majority of Israelis and Jews played into the hands of those who did not wish to distinguish between the PLO and the Abu Nidal group.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Thus, instead of an initiative to locate the Abu Nidal group in Damascus or Baghdad, the plan to invade Lebanon was activated.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO denied complicity in the attack, but Israel retaliated with punishing air and artillery strikes against Palestinian targets in Lebanon, including the PLO camps.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Sabra and the Shatila refugee camp were bombed for four hours and the local "Gaza" hospital was hit there.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] About 200 people were killed during these attacks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO hit back firing rockets at northern Israel causing considerable damage and some loss of life.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to another source, twenty villages were targeted in Galilee and 3 Israelis were wounded.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to Shlaim, Yasser Arafat, at that time being in Saudi Arabia, told the Americans through the Saudis that he was willing to suspend cross-border shelling.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] But that message was disregarded by the Israeli government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] President Reagan also sent a message to Begin urging him not to widen the attack.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 4 June the Israeli cabinet authorized a large scale invasion.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] A Mossad document declassified in 2022 revealed that planning for the invasion began in mid-1981 and that the Lebanese Christian leader Pierre Gemayel was informed of it in January 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] According to the document, Israel's Lebanon policy was mostly dictated by the military rather than the government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 6 June 1982, Israeli forces under direction of Defense Minister Ariel Sharon launched a three-pronged invasion of southern Lebanon in "Operation Peace for Galilee".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Roughly 60,000 troops and more than 800 tanks, heavily supported by aircraft, attack helicopters, artillery, and missile boats, crossed the Israel–Lebanon border in three areas.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Simultaneously, Israeli armor, paratroopers, and naval commandos set sail in amphibious landing ships from Ashdod towards the Lebanese coast north of Sidon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel's publicly stated objective was to push PLO forces back 40 kilometers (25 mi) to the north.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The westernmost Israeli force was to advance up the coastal road to Tyre.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Its mission was to bypass Tyre and destroy three PLO camps in the area, then move up the coast towards Sidon and Damour, while Israeli forces would simultaneously conduct an amphibious landing north of Sidon to cut off the retreat of PLO forces there.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, two divisions were to advance both north and south of the high ground overlooked by Beaufort Castle, which was being used as a PLO stronghold, and take the road junction at Nabatieh, while an elite reconnaissance battalion was to take the castle itself.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The two divisions were then to split, with one heading west to link up with the forces along the coast, and another towards Jezzine and from there along the right flank of Syrian forces in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The easternmost Israeli force, the largest of the three, advanced into the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Its mission was to prevent Syrian reinforcements from being sent and to stop Syrian forces from attempting to interfere with the operation on the coastal road.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The advance along the coastal road was preceded by heavy artillery bombardment and airstrikes, but quickly became bogged down and was soon behind schedule.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The narrowness of the road forced a slow advance, and Israeli armor became stuck in a large traffic jam.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Several armored vehicles were knocked out by PLO fighters with anti-tank weaponry hiding in three groves along the road.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One of the lead battalions, which was supposed to bypass Tyre and establish a blocking position to the north of the city, made a wrong turn and found itself in the center of the city, where it was ambushed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At eight in the evening the force crossed the Litani River and headed towards Sidon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the central sector, the mission went as planned.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The two Israeli divisions bypassed Beaufort Castle on both sides.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Although an order to postpone the capture of Beaufort Castle was issued, it did not reach Israeli forces in time to prevent the operation, and Israeli troops of the Golani Brigade captured the castle in the fiercely-fought Battle of the Beaufort.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The road junction at Nabatieh was also secured by the end of the first day.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Meanwhile, the easternmost force penetrated into the Bekaa Valley and bore down on the Syrian positions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] One division bypassed Mount Hermon via a road bulldozed by Israeli military engineers and cleared the town of Hasbaiya before swinging right and advancing towards Rachaiya.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Though Israeli forces halted in the floor of the valley, they were flanking Syrian forces from the east and west.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians put up minimal resistance and conducted some harassing artillery fire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the first day, the operation had gone almost entirely according to plan, though the advance along the coastal road was behind schedule.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Despite the delays, the Israeli advance along the coastal road continued steadily.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] This advance was supported by heavy air attacks against PLO positions that included the use of cluster bombs.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli missile boats also employed 76mm cannons to destroy targets along the coast, firing 3,500 shells during ten days of fighting.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli armor continued to advance towards Sidon, while other Israeli infantry attacked the three Palestinian refugee camps in the area that were used as PLO bases: Rashidiya, Burj ash-Shamali, and al-Bass.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The camps were all crisscrossed with networks of bunkers, trenches, and firing positions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis took each camp section by section using the same method: warnings were blared by loudspeaker urging civilians to leave, before air and artillery bombardment commenced, followed by an infantry assault.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry had to engage in fierce urban combat in narrow streets.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO defenders put up strong resistance and sometimes used civilians as human shields.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It took four days of combat to secure Rashidiya and three days to secure the other two camps.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the same time, an Israeli amphibious operation was conducted north of Sidon, beginning with a diversionary bombardment of targets away from the landing zone by missile boats and aircraft.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Two groups of commandos from the Shayetet 13 naval commando unit then came ashore to probe enemy defenses and secure the landing site, one of which swam to the mouth of the Awali River and another which came ashore on the landing beach in rubber dinghies.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After a brief gunbattle with armed Palestinians, the main landings began, with paratroopers coming ashore in rubber dinghies to establish a beachhead followed by three landing craft that unloaded troops and armor.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Over the following days, the three landing ships moved between Israel and Lebanon, shuttling more troops and armor onto the beachhead.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO response was limited to ineffective mortar fire, while Israeli missile boats and aircraft attacked Palestinian positions in response.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In total, about 2,400 soldiers and 400 tanks and armored personnel carriers were landed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From the beach, these forces advanced on Sidon, supported by naval gunfire from missile boats.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At the same time, Israeli forces in the central sector advanced towards Jezzine while those in the eastern sector remained in place, but began setting up heavy artillery positions that put Syrian SAM units in artillery range.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After linking up with the forces that had landed north of Sidon, while another force of paratroopers and armor with heavy air and artillery support advanced through central Sidon and cleared a south–north route through the city in fierce fighting.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another Israeli division passed through the city to link up with the forces north of Sidon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, most Israeli forces advancing towards Jezzine bypassed the town to continue advancing towards the main highway in the area, leaving a blocking force in the area that was soon joined by an armored brigade.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fighting broke out in Jezzine between the Israelis and Syrian forces holding the town.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Meanwhile, Israeli forces continued to advance along the Syrians' right flank.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces advancing along the coast also completed the capture of Sidon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Paratroopers attacked the Kasbah while a combined force of Golani Brigade infantry and tanks attacked Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Kasbah was secured in three days; the paratroopers advanced cautiously and managed to take it without suffering any casualties.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, the fighting at Ain al-Hilweh was to prove some of the fiercest of the entire war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The camp was heavily fortified and defended by PLO fighters and Islamic fundamentalists.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The defenders fought fiercely over every alley and house, with civilians who wanted to surrender shot by the fundamentalists.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli advance was slow and was supported by massive air and artillery bombardment.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF employed its previous tactics of urging civilians to leave with loudspeakers before attacking an area.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It took about eight days for the camp to fall, with the battle culminating in a last stand by the defenders at the camp mosque, which was blown up by the IDF.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In an effort to establish air superiority and greater freedom of action, the Israeli Air Force launched Operation Mole Cricket 19 on 9 June.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During the course of the operation, the Israeli Air Force scored a dramatic victory over the Syrians, shooting down 29 Syrian planes and also destroying 17 Syrian anti-aircraft missile batteries, employing electronic warfare methods to confuse and jam the Syrian radars.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis' only known losses were a single UAV shot down and two fighter jets damaged.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Later that night, an Israeli air attack destroyed a Syrian armored brigade moving south from Baalbek, and the IAF attacked and destroyed six more Syrian SAM batteries the following day.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The easternmost Israeli force, which had been stationary, resumed its advance forward up the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the center, Israeli forces were ambushed by the Syrians as they approached Ain Zhalta, and were pinned down by Syrian forces firing from superior positions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis were bogged down, and an infantry battalion was sent in by helicopter to reinforce them.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The town was only captured after a two-day armored and infantry battle.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The battle cost the Israelis 11 killed and 4 tanks, while the Syrians lost approximately 100 killed and 35 tanks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After Ain Zhalta fell, the Israelis advanced to the town of Ain Dara, which overlooked the Beirut-Damascus highway, and captured the heights overlooking the town.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Along the road to Ain Dara, the Israelis encountered Syrian tank and commando units, and found themselves bogged down as the Syrians took advantage of the terrain.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis called in air support, and Israeli attack helicopters that took advantage of ravines to fly in low beneath their targets to gain an element of surprise proved particularly effective against Syrian tanks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After a daylong battle, the Israelis had surrounded Ain Dara and were in a position to strike on the highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 10 June 1982, the Israeli air force mistook a column of IDF Nahal Brigade forces for a Syrian commando unit.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An IAF F-4 Phantom attacked the Battalion 931, advancing in open APCs in south-eastern Lebanon with cluster ammunition.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The unit suffered 24 fatalities and 108 wounded, with a further 30 soldiers shell-shocked.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the east, Israeli forces advanced along four main routes towards Joub Jannine, along both sides of the Qaraoun reservoir.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Syrian infantrymen armed with anti-tank weapons staged ambushes against Israeli tanks, and Syrian Gazelle helicopters armed with HOT missiles proved effective against Israeli armor.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, the Israelis managed to capture the valley floor, and the Syrians retreated.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis captured Rachaiya, advanced through Kfar Quoq, and took the outskirts of Yanta.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The extent of Israeli advances ensured that Syrian reinforcements were blocked from deploying west of the Qaraoun reservoir.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An Israeli armored battalion then probed past Joub Jannine to the town of Sultan Yacoub, and was ambushed by Syrian forces lying in wait.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In the Battle of Sultan Yacoub, the Israelis fought fiercely to extricate themselves, and called in reinforcements and artillery fire to cover the withdrawal.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] After six hours, the Israelis managed to retreat, having lost 10 tanks and 3 armored personnel carriers.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In addition, another major air battle erupted in which the Israeli Air Force shot down 25 Syrian jets and 4 helicopters.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] To the west, as IDF troops mopped up remaining resistance in Tyre and Sidon, the Israeli advance on Beirut continued, and Syrian tank and commando units were then deployed south of Beirut to reinforce the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] When the Israelis reached the Beirut suburb of Kafr Sill, they met a joint Syrian-PLO force for the first time, and fought a difficult battle to take it.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF temporarily halted its advance in the western sector at Kafr Sill.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 June, Israel and Syria announced that they had agreed to a cease-fire at noon, which would not include the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The cease-fire was to come into effect at noon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Just before the cease-fire was to take effect, the Syrians moved a column of T-72 tanks so as to position it against Israeli forces in the valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry teams armed with BGM-71 TOW anti-tank missiles ambushed the Syrian column, destroying 11 tanks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another air battle also occurred, with the Israelis shooting down 18 more Syrian jets.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli advance on Beirut pressed forward in the west, reaching Khalde on 11 June.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Six miles south of Beirut, the town was the last PLO position in front of Beirut Airport.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO fighters, led by Abdullah Siyam, fought a rearguard action which held up the Israeli advance for six days.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis, who stood on the outskirts of Beirut, advanced towards the airport, and engaged in frequent combat with PLO and Syrian units as Israeli warplanes continued to bomb PLO positions in Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The PLO's situation gradually grew worse as the Israeli advance gained ground, threatening to trap the PLO and a Syrian brigade deployed with them in the city.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 12 June, the Israeli-Syrian cease-fire was extended to the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the Israeli advance halted, the Israelis turned their attention to the zone they already occupied in southern Lebanon, and began a policy to root out any PLO remnants.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli troops began searches for arms caches, and suspected PLO members were systematically rounded up and screened, and taken to a detention camp on the Amoun Heights.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 13 June, less than twelve hours after the Israeli-PLO ceasefire had gone into effect, it fell apart, and heavy fighting erupted around Khalde.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the fighting raged, an IDF armored unit struck northeast, attempting to bypass Khalde and advance on Baabda, which overlooked the airport and could be used as another staging point to cut the Beirut-Damascus highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 14 June, Syrian forces were being deployed to Khalde.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Syrian units in Beirut and three commando battalions armed with anti-tank weaponry took up defensive positions southwest of the airport to block any Israeli attempt to capture it.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis attempted to flank these defenses by moving off the road past Shuweifat, up a narrow, steep, and winding road towards Baabda, but were ambushed by a Syrian commando battalion.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians attacked Israeli armor with rocket-propelled grenades and anti-tank missiles at close range.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli infantry dismounted and engaged the Syrians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Fierce fighting took place, with the Israelis calling in artillery at very close range to themselves.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis advanced relentlessly, and after fourteen hours of fierce combat that raged up through Ain Aanoub and Souq el-Gharb, they broke through the Syrian positions and entered Baabda.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF then immediately sent reinforcements to the column in Baabda to enable it to carry out further operations.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From Baabda, the Israeli force split into three columns, one of which struck across the highway and entered the mountainous area to the northeast, one swung west and took up positions in the steep hills west of Beirut, and one turned toward Kahale, which was further down the highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] To the south, the IDF drove PLO forces out of Shuweifat, but no major battles occurred.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis had now cut the Beirut-Damascus highway, cutting off all PLO and Syrian forces in the city.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 15 June, Israel offered free passage to all Syrian forces in Beirut if they would withdraw from the city to the Bekaa Valley in the east, but the Syrian government refused and sent further reinforcements to its units along the highway and north of the highway near Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis faced Syrian strongpoints reinforced by armor and artillery all along the highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, between 16 June and 22 June, the fighting was limited to artillery duels and minor firefights between Israeli and Syrian forces, as both sides reinforced their troops.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the two sides prepared for combat, the IDF deemed capturing the Beirut–Damascus highway to be of critical importance.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 22 June, the IDF launched an operation to capture the highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli Air Force flew highly effective missions against Syrian positions and vehicles, with Israeli pilots reporting 130 enemy vehicles destroyed in a single air attack alone.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli long-range artillery targeted Syrian strongpoints to the north.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli armored forces with artillery support attacked Syrian positions along the highway, with the objective of driving them from the highway all the way back to the edge of the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] With air and artillery support mostly limited to targets north of the highway, the fighting was fierce, especially to the south.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the day, Israel accepted an American request for a cease-fire and halted its offensive, but the cease-fire collapsed the following day and the fighting resumed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] As the Israelis pushed forward, and managed to trap a large Syrian force, Syrian defenses began to collapse.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] For the first time in the war, Syrian troops began to break and run.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] At Aley, which was defended by Iranian volunteers sent to fight for the PLO, the Israelis encountered fierce resistance.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis managed to push to the eastern Bekaa Valley, and on 24 June, began to shell the outskirts of Chtaura, which was at the northern mouth of the Bekaa Valley and served as headquarters of all Syrian forces there.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] It was also the last major obstacle before the Syrian border, as well as Syria's capital Damascus itself.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis managed to reach the mountain pass near the village of Dahr el-Baidar, which was the last obstacle before Cthaura.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians fought fiercely to hold the pass, and the Israeli advance halted, with the Israelis holding their ground and harassing the Syrians with artillery fire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By 25 June, with the remaining Syrian positions on and north of the highway no longer tenable, the Syrians withdrew.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis allowed the withdrawal to occur but conducted artillery harassment and continued to shell the outskirts of Chtaura.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Syrians attempted to deploy a SAM battery in the Bekaa Valley at midnight, but Israeli intelligence detected this, and the battery was destroyed in an Israeli air attack.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] By the end of the day, a cease-fire was announced.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis stopped at their present positions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Siege of Beirut had begun on 14 June 1982: Israeli forces had completed the encirclement of the city the previous day.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israelis chose to keep the city under siege rather than forcibly capture it, as they were unwilling to accept the heavy casualties that the heavy street fighting required to capture the city would have resulted in.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces bombarded targets within Beirut from land, sea, and air, and attempted to assassinate Palestinian leaders through airstrikes.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The Israeli Navy maintained a blockade on the port of Beirut with a ring of missile boats and patrol boats supported by submarines.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The siege lasted until August, when an agreement was reached in August 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] More than 14,000 PLO combatants evacuated the country in August and September, supervised by the Multinational Force in Lebanon, an international peacekeeping force with troops from the United States, United Kingdom, France, and Italy.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] About 6,500 Fatah fighters relocated from Beirut to Jordan, Syria, Iraq, Sudan, both North and South Yemen, Greece, and Tunisia—the latter of which became the new PLO headquarters.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel withdrew its forces from west Beirut on 29 September, officially ending Operation Peace for Galilee.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Philip Habib, Ronald Reagan's envoy to Lebanon, provided an understanding (i.e., assurance) to the PLO that the Palestinian civilians in the refugee camps would not be harmed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, increased hostilities against the US resulted in the April 1983 United States Embassy bombing.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In response, the US brokered the May 17 Agreement, in an attempt to stall hostilities between Israel and Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, this agreement eventually failed to take shape, and hostilities continued.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] These attacks were attributed to Iranian-backed Islamist guerrillas.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following this incident, international peacekeeping forces were withdrawn from Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Following the departure of the PLO and international peacekeepers, Islamist militants began launching guerrilla attacks against Israeli forces.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Suicide bombings were a particularly popular tactic, the most serious being the Tyre headquarters bombings, which twice devastated IDF headquarters in Tyre, and killed 103 Israeli soldiers, border policemen, and Shin Bet agents, as well as 49–56 Lebanese.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The IDF subsequently withdrew from the Shouf Mountains but continued occupying Lebanon south of the Awali River.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] An increased number of Islamic militias began operating in South Lebanon, launching guerrilla attacks on Israeli positions and on pro-Israeli Lebanese militias.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israeli forces often responded with increased security measures and airstrikes on militant positions, and casualties on all sides steadily climbed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In a vacuum left with eradication of PLO, the disorganized Islamic militants in South Lebanon began to consolidate.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] The emerging Hezbollah, soon to become the preeminent Islamic militia, evolved during this period.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] However, scholars disagree as to when Hezbollah came to be regarded as a distinct entity.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Over time, a number of Shi'a group members were slowly assimilated into the organization, such as Islamic Jihad members, Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, and the Revolutionary Justice Organization.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In February 1985, Israel withdrew from Sidon and turned it over to the Lebanese Army, but faced attacks: 15 Israelis were killed and 105 wounded during the withdrawal.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Dozens of pro-Israeli Lebanese militiamen were also assassinated.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] From mid-February to mid-March, the Israelis lost 18 dead and 35 wounded.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 11 March, Israeli forces raided the town of Zrariyah, killing 40 Amal fighters and capturing a large stock of arms.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] On 9 April, a Shiite girl drove a car bomb into an IDF convoy, and the following day, a soldier was killed by a land mine.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] During that same period, Israeli forces killed 80 Lebanese guerrillas in five weeks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Another 1,800 Shi'as were taken as prisoners.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Israel withdrew from the Bekaa valley on 24 April, and from Tyre on the 29th.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] In June 1985, the IDF unilaterally withdrew to a security zone in southern Lebanon along with its principal Lebanese ally, the South Lebanon Army, completing its troop withdrawal to the security zone on 5 June.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Despite this being considered the end of the war, conflict would continue.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p01] Hezbollah continued to fight the IDF and SLA in the South Lebanon conflict until Israel's final withdrawal from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the course of combat operations, the Israeli Air Force conducted successful ground attack missions against Syrian and PLO targets, with Israeli attack helicopters inflicting heavy losses on Syrian armor.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli jets shot down between 82 and 86 Syrian aircraft in aerial combat, without losses.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] A single Israeli A-4 Skyhawk and two helicopters were shot down by anti-aircraft fire and SAM missiles.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This was the largest aerial combat battle of the jet age with over 150 fighters from both sides engaged.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syrian claims of aerial victories were met with skepticism even from their Soviet allies.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Soviets were so shaken by the staggering losses sustained by their allies that they dispatched the deputy head of their air defense force to Syria to examine how the Israelis had been so dominant.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli Air Force also performed ground attacks, notably destroying the majority of Syrian anti-aircraft batteries stationed in Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] AH-1 Cobra helicopter gunships were employed against Syrian armour and fortifications.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IAF Cobras destroyed dozens of Syrian Armored fighting vehicles, including some of the modern Soviet T-72 main battle tanks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The war also witnessed the Israeli Merkava MBT make its first combat debut, facing Syrian T-72 tanks.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During these engagements, the Israelis claimed that the Merkava proved superior to the T-72, destroying a number of them without sustaining a single loss to T-72 fire.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] However, defense analysts and the Syrians claimed the opposite, saying that their T-72s were highly effective and that none were lost.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The T-72 tanks of the Syrian 2nd Armored Division were credited with not only halting the advance of an Israeli armored brigade on Rashaya on 10 June but pushing them back.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They tallied the destruction of 33 tanks and the capture of an M60 Patton, which was sent to Damascus and thence transported to Moscow.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syrian tanks saw similar success against Israeli armor in Ain Zhalta and Sultan Yacoub in fighting on 8–10 June, stemming their advance to capture the Beirut-Damascus highway.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 14 September 1982, Bachir Gemayel, the newly elected President of Lebanon, was assassinated by Habib Shartouni of the Syrian Social Nationalist Party.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli forces occupied West Beirut the next day.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] At that time, the Lebanese Christian Militia, also known as the Phalangists, were allied with Israel.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli command authorized the entrance of a force of approximately 150 Phalangist fighters' into Sabra and the Shatila refugee camp.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Between 460 and 3,500 civilians, mostly Palestinians and Lebanese Shiites were massacred by the Phalangists, who themselves suffered only two casualties.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese army's chief prosecutor investigated the killings and counted 460 dead, Israeli intelligence estimated 700–800 dead, and the Palestinian Red Crescent claimed 2,000 dead.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 1,200 death certificates were issued to anyone who produced three witnesses claiming a family member disappeared during the time of the massacre.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli troops surrounded the camps with tanks and checkpoints, monitoring entrances and exits.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli investigation by the Kahan Commission of Inquiry found that Ariel Sharon bore "personal responsibility" for failing to prevent the massacre, and for failing to act once he learned of the massacre.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Commission recommended that he be removed as Defense Minister and that he never hold a position in any future Israeli government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Sharon initially ignored the call to resign, but after the death of an anti-war protester, resigned as Israel's Defense Minister, remaining in Begin's cabinet as a Minister without portfolio.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The 1982 Lebanon War was at first a conventional war up to and including when the PLO were expelled from Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The war was limited by both Israel and Syria because they were determined to isolate the fighting, not allowing it to turn into an all-out war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli forces were numerically superior, allowing Israel to maintain both the initiative and an element of surprise.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Syrian Army fielded six divisions and 500 aircraft, while Israel used five divisions and two brigades, plus 600 aircraft.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] There were numerous other factions involved.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IDF forces totalled 78,000 men, 1,240 tanks and 1,500 armoured personnel carriers.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] IDF troops were deployed in five divisions and two reinforced brigade-size units.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF maintained additional forces on the Golan Heights as an area reserve.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Syrian Army had over 30,000 troops deployed in Lebanon in June 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The largest concentration was in the Bekaa Valley where the 1st Armoured Division consisting of the 58th Mechanised and the 76th and 91st Armoured Brigades.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The 62nd Independent Armored Brigade and ten commando battalions were also assigned to the division.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria deployed around 400 tanks in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 19 surface-to-air missile batteries, including SA6's, were also deployed in the Bekaa Valley.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In Beirut and the Shouf Mountains were the 85th Infantry Brigade, the PLA, As-Sa'iqa and 20 commando battalions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria deployed around 200 tanks in this area.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Their primary mission was to protect the Beirut-Damascus Highway, which was Syria's primary supply line in the region.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian Liberation Organization forces continued to grow in Lebanon, with full-time military personnel numbering around 15,000 fedayeen, although only 6,000 of these – including 4,500 regulars – deployed in the south.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They were armed with 80 aging tanks, many of them no longer mobile, and with 100 to 200 pieces of artillery.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Israeli analysts Schiff and Ya'ari (1984), the PLO more than quadrupled its artillery from 80 cannons and rocket launchers in July 1981 to 250 in June 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] PLO primary forces consisted of three conventional brigades – each of 2,000 to 2,500 men – and of seven artillery battalions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Each brigade comprised contingents of the many PLO factions.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Yarmouk Brigade was stationed along the coastal strip while the Kastel Brigade was in the south.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Karameh Brigade was stationed on the eastern slopes of Mount Hermon in the area called Fatahland.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Heavy weapons consisted of about 60 T-34, T-54 and T-55 tanks (most of them dug in as pillboxes), up to 250 130mm and 155 mm artillery, many BM21 Katyusha multiple-rocket launchers plus heavy mortars.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian groups of the radical Rejectionist Front joined forces with the mainstream PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Left wing parties joined forces with the PLO in what came to be known as the "joint forces".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The first UNIFIL troops were deployed in the area on 23 March 1978.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] These troops were reassigned from other UN peacekeeping operations in the area, namely the United Nations Emergency Force and the United Nations Disengagement Observer Force Zone.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the 1982 Lebanon War, UN positions were overrun, primarily by the South Lebanon Army forces under Saad Haddad.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Estimates of numbers of the casualties in the conflict vary widely.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the end of the first week, 14 June 1982, International Red Cross and Lebanese police figures said that 9,583 had died and 16,608 injured.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the end of the second week, they said up to 14,000 people died and 20,000 were injured, mostly civilians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] During the Siege of Beirut, by late August 1982, Lebanese sources put the death toll in Beirut at 6,776.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This figure included victims of the 4 June 1982, bombing, which occurred two days before the operation officially started.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Lebanese police and international doctors serving in Beirut put the number of civilian casualties at about 80%.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to American military analyst Richard Gabriel, all factions in the conflicts agree that between 4,000 and 5,000 civilians died during the siege caused by military activity of all sides.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] He states that most of the observers that were present on the ground and other relevant sources in Lebanon agree that estimates of 8,000–10,000 are too high.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Accurate numbers of total casualties are hard to estimate, due to "[t]he chaos of warfare, the destruction of city neighborhoods and refugee camps, the haste with which bodies were buried in mass graves and the absence of impartial agencies".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Many officials in Beirut, including those of the International Red Cross, claimed that the number of deaths were extremely difficult to estimate correctly.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] At least one official from a relief organization claimed that in the South about 80% of deaths were civilian and only 20% military.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In early September 1982, the independent Beirut newspaper *An Nahar* published an estimate of deaths from hospital and police records covering the period from 6 June to 31 August 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] It claimed that 17,285 people were killed: 5,515 people, both military and civilian, in the Beirut area; and 2,513 civilians, as well as 9,797 military forces, including PLO and Syrians, outside of the Beirut area.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Lebanese authorities gave a figure of 19,085 killed and 30,000 wounded; in Beirut alone 6,775 died, 84% of them civilians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In southern Lebanon, around 20% of those dead were civilians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] They do not include the estimated 800–3,500 killed in the Sabra and Shatila massacre.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Richard Gabriel estimated that roughly 2,400 PLO fighters were killed during the war, of whom about 1,400 were killed throughout southern Lebanon and another 1,000 killed during the Siege of Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Gabriel also estimated that between 5,000 and 8,000 civilians died during the war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Some later estimates have put the total figure at 18–19,000 killed and more than 30,000 wounded, most of them civilians.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 80% of villages in South Lebanon were damaged, with some completely destroyed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli government maintained that about 1,000 Palestinian fighters and 800 Lebanese civilians died during the invasion, excluding the siege of Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Anthony Tucker-Jones estimated that about 1,500 PLO fighters were killed.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Kenneth Pollack estimated that 1,200 Syrian soldiers were killed and about 3,000 wounded during the war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Israeli figures, Israeli losses in Operation Peace for Galilee were 368 dead and 2,383 wounded, from 6 June until 10 October.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The highest ranking IDF casualty of the war was Brigadier General Yekutiel Adam, who was Deputy Chief of Staff of the IDF and had been appointed to be the next Director-General of the Mossad.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] He was killed by a Palestinian fighter while seeking protection in a house in Dawha, near Damour, during a mortar attack.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Other Israeli fatalities included one Colonel, two Lieutenant Colonels; 19 Majors, 28 Captains, 46 Lieutenants, 132 Sergeants, 90 Corporals, and 49 Privates.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Kenneth Pollack, Israeli losses in action against the Syrians were 195 dead and 872 wounded.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 130 Israeli tanks were destroyed or damaged by the Syrians, as were 175 APCs.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF also listed six soldiers as Missing in action in the Battle of Sultan Yacoub.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Two prisoners and the bodies of another two were later returned to Israel but two soldiers remain missing.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Palestinian factions captured 11 IDF soldiers during the war, including one of the soldiers missing from Sultan Yacoub, an Israeli Air Force pilot in the Beaufort battle, a soldier during the Siege of Beirut and eight soldiers in the raid on an IDF observation post in Bhamdoun.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] All eleven prisoners were subsequently released in prisoner exchanges.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF's total casualties in Lebanon from the start of Operation Peace for Galilee in June 1982 to the withdrawal to the security zone in June 1985 amounted 654 killed and 3,887 wounded.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The IDF continued to occupy a substantial part of Lebanon even after the withdrawal to security zone in June 1985.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Resistance continued and IDF losses continued to mount.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By the time IDF withdrew from Lebanon in May 2000 the total number of IDF fatalities had reached 1,216 killed since June 1982.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israeli civilian casualties from cross-border shelling numbered 9–10 killed and at least 248 wounded between June 1982 and 1999.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In September 1982, the PLO withdrew most of its forces from Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] With U.S. assistance, Israel and Lebanon reached an accord in May 1983, that set the stage to withdraw Israeli forces from Lebanon while letting them patrol a "security zone" together with the Lebanese Army.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The instruments of ratification were never exchanged, and in March 1984, under pressure from Syria, Lebanon cancelled the agreement.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In January 1985, Israel started to withdraw most of its troops, leaving a small residual Israeli force and an Israeli-supported militia, the South Lebanon Army in southern Lebanon in a "security zone", which Israel considered a necessary buffer against attacks on its northern territory.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli withdrawal to the security zone ended in June 1985.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israel withdrew fully from Lebanon in 2000.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The political vacuum resulting from the 1985 Israeli withdrawal would eventually lead to the *de facto* Syrian occupation of Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria would gain much more power over Lebanon than what it enjoyed before 1982, but it would no longer align with the PLO.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In the War of the Camps that followed the Israeli withdrawal, Syria fought their former Palestinian allies.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Following Arafat's decision of June 1982, by September 1982, the PLO had withdrawn most of its forces from West Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Syria backed the anti-Arafat PLO forces of Abu Musa in the Beka valley from May 1983.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] When Arafat castigated the Syrian government for blocking PLO supplies in June 1983, the Syrian government declared Arafat a *persona non-grata* on 24 June 1983.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] With the withdrawal of the PLO leadership from Tripoli in December 1983 there was an Egyptian-PLO rapprochement, this was found to be encouraging by the Reagan administration but was condemned by the Israeli government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Ariel Sharon requested permission for a military operation that would only go 25 miles into Lebanon, and would only be for 2–3 days.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On this basis, nearly the entire Knesset voted in favor of going to war.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Only Hadash opposed the war, and even submitted a no-confidence motion against the Israeli government.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Hadash Knesset member Meir Vilner said in the Knesset plenary session that: "The government is leading Israel to an abyss.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] It is doing something that in the course of time might lead to crying for generations".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In response, they were condemned, and calls were heard, among others from the editor of Yediot Ahronoth, to prosecute them for treason.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Left-wing Knesset members, including Shulamit Aloni and Yossi Sarid, were absent from the plenary for the vote.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Even the Labor faction voted in support.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] By mid January 1983 Rabin was saying that the Israeli attempt to impose a peace agreement on Lebanon by the use of force was a "mistake" based upon an "illusion".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Heavy Israeli casualties, alleged disinformation of Israeli government leaders and the Israeli public by Israeli military, as well as political advocates of the campaign and lack of clear goals led to increasing disquiet among Israelis.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This culminated in a large protest rally in Tel Aviv on 25 September 1982, organized by the Peace Now movement, following the 1982 Sabra and Shatila massacre.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Organizers claimed 400,000 people participated in the rally, and it became known as the "400,000 rally".
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Other estimates put the figure much lower, maybe reaching 100,000 Israelis but including thousands of reserve soldiers back from Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Israeli-Maronite alliance dissolved, and Sharon's goal of installing a pro-Israel Christian government in Beirut was not accomplished.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] 850,000 Christians emigrated out of Lebanon during the Civil War, most of them permanently.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] This heavily impacted the civilian population from both sides, with more than 5,000 killed from both sides.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The Mountain War ended after the Christian forces and civilians withdrew to the town of Deir el Kamar, where they were besieged for 3 months before all hostilities ceased and they were transported to East Beirut.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The invasion led to the switching of sides of Amal Movement, which used to fight against the PLO prior to the invasion.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The invasion is also popularly held to be the major catalyst for the creation of the Iranian and Syrian supported Hezbollah organization, which by 1991 was the sole armed militia in Lebanon not supported by Israel and by 2000 had completely replaced the vanquished PLO in Southern Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] According to Abraham Rabinovich, the complete dominance of U.S. and Israeli technology and tactics over those of the Eastern Bloc was a factor that hastened the demise of the Warsaw Pact and the Soviet Union.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] However, this was not the first confrontation in which Soviet weaponry had been outmatched by American weaponry.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In many of the Cold War conflicts the Americans and their allies had superior technology.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Nonetheless, the gap between the First World and Second World weaponry was more apparent in the 1980s and weighed more heavily on Second World leaders.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] One of the lingering consequences of the Israeli invasion of Lebanon was the creation of Hezbollah.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In 2000, when Ehud Barak was Israeli Prime Minister, Israel withdrew from the security zone to behind the Blue Line.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Lebanon and Hezbollah continue to claim a small area called Shebaa Farms as Lebanese territory, but Israel insists that it is captured Syrian territory with the same status as the Golan Heights.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The United Nations has not determined the final status of Shebaa Farms but has determined that Israel has complied with UNSC resolution 425.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The UN Secretary-General had concluded that, as of 16 June 2000, Israel had withdrawn its forces from Lebanon in accordance with UN Security Council Resolution 425 of 1978, bringing closure to the 1982 invasion as far as the UN was concerned.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon led to pressure on the Syrians to withdraw their occupation forces and this pressure intensified after the assassination of the popular Lebanese Prime Minister, Rafik Hariri.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 26 April 2005 the Syrian occupation forces withdrew from Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] On 16 December 1982, the United Nations General Assembly condemned the Sabra and Shatila massacre and declared it to be an act of genocide.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The voting record on section D of Resolution 37/123, which "resolves that the massacre was an act of genocide", was: yes: 123; no: 0; abstentions: 22; non-voting: 12.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] The abstentions were: Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany (Federal Republic), Iceland, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Sweden, United Kingdom, U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Israel, Ivory Coast, Papua New Guinea, Barbados and Dominican Republic.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Some delegates disputed the claim that the massacre constituted genocide.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] In 1982, an international commission investigated into reported violations of International Law by Israel during its invasion of the Lebanon.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Chairman was Seán MacBride, the other members were Richard A.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Falk, Kader Asmal, Brian Bercusson, Géraud de la Pradelle, and Stefan Wild.
[src:siege/1982-lebanon-war-p02] Following a four-month investigation, on 8 February 1983, the Kahan Commission submitted its report, which was released to the public by spokesman Bezalel Gordon simultaneously in Hebrew and English.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] MOVE members shot at Philadelphia police who had come to evict them from the house they were using as their headquarters.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Philadelphia police aviators then dropped two explosive devices from a Pennsylvania State Police helicopter onto the roof of the house, which was occupied at the time.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] For 90 minutes, the Philadelphia Police Department allowed the resulting fire to burn out of control, destroying 61 previously evacuated neighboring houses over two city blocks and leaving 250 people homeless.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Six adults and five children were killed in the attack; two occupants of the house, one adult and one child, survived.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] A lawsuit in federal court found that the city used excessive force and violated constitutional protections against unreasonable search and seizure.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 1981, MOVE relocated to a row house at 6221 Osage Avenue in the Cobbs Creek area of West Philadelphia.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Neighbors complained to the city for years about trash around their building, confrontations with neighbors, and bullhorn announcements of political messages by MOVE members.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The bullhorn was broken and inoperable for the three weeks prior to the police bombing of the row house.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The police obtained arrest warrants in 1985 charging four MOVE occupants with crimes including parole violations, contempt of court, illegal possession of firearms, and making terroristic threats.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Mayor Wilson Goode and police commissioner Gregore J.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Sambor classified MOVE as a terrorist organization.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Police evacuated residents of the area from the neighborhood prior to their action.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Residents were told that they would be able to return after 24 hours.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] On Monday, May 13, 1985, nearly 500 police officers, along with city manager Leo Brooks, arrived in force and attempted to clear the building and execute the arrest warrants.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Water and electricity were shut off to try to force MOVE members out of the house.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] At 5:35 a.m., Sambor read a long speech addressed to MOVE members that started with, "Attention MOVE: This is America.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] You have to abide by the laws of the United States." They were given 15 minutes to come out.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] When the MOVE members did not respond, the police decided to forcibly remove everyone who was in the house.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Inside the building were seven adults and six children.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Police threw tear gas canisters at the building.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The MOVE members fired at them, and a gunfight with semi-automatic and automatic firearms went on for 90 minutes.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] One officer's flak jacket was hit in the back, but he was not seriously hurt.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Police used more than 10,000 rounds of ammunition.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] At 2 p.m., Sambor ordered that the compound be bombed.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] From a Pennsylvania State Police helicopter, Philadelphia Police Department Lt.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Frank Powell proceeded to drop two 1.5-pound (0.75 kg) bombs (which the police referred to as "entry devices") made of Tovex, a dynamite substitute, combined with two pounds of FBI-supplied C-4, targeting a fortified, bunker-like cubicle on the roof of the house.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The bombs exploded after 45 seconds, igniting the fuel of a gasoline-powered generator and setting the house on fire, which was left to burn.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Officials later stated that this was to let the fire burn through the roof and destroy the "bunker", so police could then drop tear gas into the house and flush out the occupants.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Thirty minutes later, firefighters moved in to control the fire, but there was gunfire and the firefighters and police were ordered back as the fire spread to neighboring houses down the street.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The only two MOVE survivors, Birdie Africa, who was 13 at the time, and Ramona Africa, both escaped the house.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Police initially said that two men had also run out of the house at the same time and fired at them and that police had returned fire.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Ramona Africa said that police fired at those trying to escape.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Police said that MOVE members moved in and out of the house shooting at the police.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The fire department declared the fire under control at 11:47 p.m.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The fire killed 11 of the people in the house, six adults and five children: John Africa, Rhonda Africa, Theresa Africa, Frank Africa, Conrad Africa, Tree Africa, Delisha Africa, Netta Africa, Little Phil Africa, Tomaso Africa, and Raymond Africa.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Sixty-one neighboring houses were destroyed by the fire, leaving 250 people homeless.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Mayor Goode appointed an investigative commission called the Philadelphia Special Investigation Commission (PSIC, which became known as the MOVE Commission), chaired by William H.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Commissioner Sambor resigned in November 1985; in a speech the following year, he said that he was made a "surrogate" by Goode.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 1986, Ellen Powell Tiberino and her husband Joseph created a seven-foot relief sculpture called *The MOVE Confrontation* as their interpretation of the bombing.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] It depicted people engulfed in flames, Mayor W.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Wilson Goode, a death mask and horrified spectators.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] It created controversy in the city and produced headlines across the country.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The MOVE Commission issued its report on March 6, 1986.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The report denounced the actions of the city government, stating that dropping a bomb on an occupied row house was unconscionable.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Following the release of the report, Goode made a formal public apology.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] No one from the city government was criminally charged in the attack.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The only surviving adult MOVE member, Ramona Africa, refused to testify in court and was charged and convicted on charges of riot and conspiracy; she served seven years in prison.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] A lawsuit appealing a judgment against the police and public officials was filed with the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit on November 3, 1994 *Africa v.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] City of Philadelphia* (In re City of Philadelphia Litig.), 49 F.3d 945 (1995) and was decided on March 6, 1995.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 1996, a federal jury ordered the city to pay a $1.5 million civil suit judgment to survivor Ramona Africa and relatives of two people killed in the bombing.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The jury had found that the city used excessive force and violated the members' constitutional protections against unreasonable search and seizure.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Ramona was awarded $500,000 for the pain, suffering and physical harm suffered in the fire.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 2005, federal judge Clarence Charles Newcomer presided over a civil trial brought by residents seeking damages for having been displaced by the widespread destruction following the 1985 police bombing of MOVE.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] A jury decided that the City of Philadelphia should pay them $12.83 million.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 2013, the documentary film *Let the Fire Burn* introduced the history of the MOVE bombing to a wider audience.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The opera *We Shall Not Be Moved* (2017), with music by Daniel Bernard Roumain, lyrics by Marc Bamuthi Joseph and choreography by Bill T.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In November 2020, the Philadelphia City Council approved a resolution to formally apologize for the MOVE bombing.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] On May 8, 2025, the Philadelphia City Council approved a resolution declaring May 13 as "a day of reflection and remembrance" in honor of the victims.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] By late fall 1985, the city government and a private developer had begun to rebuild the residential block that the police department damaged with the MOVE bombing.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] However, the homeowners who moved back in found the construction to be of poor quality, and in 1995, the Ed Rendell administration summoned the United States Army Corps of Engineers to inspect the buildings; they found the 61 buildings were not up to code.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The city government attempted to remedy this, but by 2005, the city gave up trying to improve the defects and offered $150,000 to any resident who would agree to leave; over two-thirds accepted the deal and abandoned their houses.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 2016, the city government committed to rebuilding the block again; in January 2023, Mike Africa Jr., who is a member of MOVE and great-nephew of John Africa, bought the house at 6221 Osage Avenue with plans to turn part of it into a memorial.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Since the bombing, the bones of two children, 14-year-old Tree (Katricia Dotson) and 12-year-old Delisha Orr Africa, were kept at the University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In 2021, *Billy Penn* revealed that according to the museum, the remains had been transferred to researchers at Princeton University, though the university was unaware of their exact whereabouts.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The remains had been used by Janet Monge, an adjunct professor in anthropology at the University of Pennsylvania and a visiting professor in the same subject at Princeton University, in videos for an online forensics course named "Real *Bones*: Adventures in Forensic Anthropology," as case studies.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] A day after Farley's resignation, staff at the Medical Examiner's Office found the box labeled "MOVE" in a refrigerated area of their office containing the un-cremated remains.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] As of 2021, Mike Africa Jr. stated that the Africa family have not yet decided what to do with the remains.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The sisters' remains from the Medical Examiner's Office were released to their surviving brother in August 2022.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] A legal team hired by the University of Pennsylvania stated that the bones of Delisha Orr were never at the Penn Museum.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] However, an investigation by the City of Philadelphia disagreed, and stated that there was evidence that remains of Delisha Orr were at the Penn Museum.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] Nine forensic anthropologists certified by the American Board of Forensic Anthropology disagreed with the claims published by Penn's legal team and agreed with those of the City of Philadelphia.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] The City of Philadelphia also questioned whether all the remains of Katricia Dotson which were at the Penn Museum were given to MOVE in 2021.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] In November 2024, further remains were found at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:siege/1985-move-bombing] They were thought to belong to Delisha Africa.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The **1997 Roby standoff**, sometimes referred to as "**Roby Ridge**", was a standoff that occurred over the course of 39 days from September 22 to October 31, 1997, in Roby, Illinois, involving law enforcement and Shirley Allen, a 51-year-old woman resisting involuntary commitment.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] It is one of the longest single-person standoffs in history, and was the longest standoff in the history of the Illinois State Police.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The standoff was the subject of a minor media circus in late 1997, and Allen was supported by libertarians and the American militia movement, some of whom traveled to Roby to support her.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The only casualty of the standoff was a police dog that was shot and wounded by Allen.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen's family became increasingly concerned with her delusions and so-called "erratic behavior".
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Convinced she needed psychiatric care, Allen's family asked the district attorney for help, and the court ordered Allen into involuntary commitment in Springfield.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen supporters, including one of her close friends, claim that Allen's mental decline had been exaggerated by her family and that they sought her institutionalization to gain ownership over her 47-acre property, which contained two oil wells.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] On September 22, 1997, three Christian County Sheriff's Office deputies arrived at Allen's house to serve the commitment papers.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Accompanying the deputies was their friend Byron Dugger, Allen's brother.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] When the deputies knocked on her door, Allen answered holding a bolt action shotgun.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The deputies and Duggan retreated to call for assistance from the Illinois State Police (ISP), who surrounded her property and initiated a standoff.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] ISP Director Terrance Gainer chose to simply wait for Allen to surrender, and stated police were "there for this woman's protection and for the protection of her neighbors.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Over the course of the siege, which lasted 39 days, sheriff's deputies and state troopers tried numerous methods to coax Allen out of her house.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] At first, deputies fired 40 mm tear gas rounds into her house, hoping to smoke her out; however, Allen, familiar with the effects of tear gas from her medical career, covered herself in petroleum jelly and a wet towel, protecting her from the irritants in the gas.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Attempts at using rubber bullets to stun her also failed, as she wore several layers of clothing stuffed with pillows and magazines, as well as multiple hats, ensuring they had little effect.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] When a police dog was sent to distract and calm Allen, she fired at it with her shotgun, wounding it.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The utilities to Allen's property were also cut, again to little effect: she was using battery-powered devices, subsided on a preexisting stockpile of canned food, and had already been relying on bottled water after her property's well ran dry.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen fired two shots over the course of the siege, but otherwise she stayed quiet inside her house for the majority of it, rarely venturing out onto her deck.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Attempts at negotiating with her failed, as she refused to communicate with anyone outside her house.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] After several weeks of no progress, Gainer decided the best course of action was to have police withdraw from sight and monitor her from a distance, in the hopes that Allen would calm down and "resume a normal, unarmed routine".
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] In an apparent attempt to "soothe her", police began to loudly play classical music and songs by Barry Manilow (apparently her favorite genre and music artist respectively) over speakers toward Allen's house.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Hidden cameras were also placed on her property, including one hidden in a bucket on her back porch, but Allen would frequently notice them and cut their wires, disabling them.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] As the standoff dragged on, police presence and actions began to frustrate Roby residents, as well as libertarians and militiamen from across the United States, and a small but vocal group of Allen sympathizers emerged.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Several supporters traveled to Roby to show their support for Allen and hold rallies demanding police leave her alone.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Some people tried to get a closer look to see what was going on or, in the case of one onlooker who camped outside police barricades for most of the siege, to ensure police did not harm or abuse her.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] One neighbor was arrested for trying to sneak onto Allen's property to deliver her food and water, while others paid her bills for her.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Supporters and the media coined a nickname for the standoff: "Roby Ridge", evoking the 1992 Ruby Ridge standoff in Idaho that was a cause célèbre for the militia movement, although police discouraged its use.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] In an attempt to calm Allen's supporters, Gainer contacted J.J.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Johnson, a former militia leader, and Jack McLamb, a former police officer who was present at the Ruby Ridge standoff, who had both traveled to Roby to protest the police siege.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] After Gainer met with them and discussed his perspective, Johnson and McLamb came around to understand police actions, but their attempts at expressing this at a rally led to the protestors labeling them traitors.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Responding to criticisms of excessive time and cost, Gainer explained that while it would probably have been justifiable to raid Allen's property early, they would simply be criticized for being aggressive instead, and that he was willing to be patient if it meant Allen's life would be at less risk.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] On October 31, around noon, police heard what they believed was Allen loading her shotgun, and advanced to her house.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] She stepped onto her back porch twice to leave out trays of food and water that police had regularly left for her.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] She then stepped out a third time to cut the bucket camera's wire, but struggled to do so.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] A trooper positioned near her porch saw the glint of the scissors in Allen's hand and, believing it was a firearm, fired six rubber bullets at her, striking her with three bullets in her leg, side, and chest.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen fell to the ground, where she was subdued and detained in plastic handcuffs.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] After being handcuffed, Allen was consoled by a trooper and led to the front of her house, where she conversed with police and relatives.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] She reportedly "slipped in and out of rational conversation", during which she claimed there were helicopters telling her to stay inside, and made her relatives open their mouths so she could see their teeth and lips to ensure they were not wearing masks.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] When police learned that she had not consumed anything in three days, they offered her a drink, but Allen refused, claiming the helicopters were insisting it was poisonous; after a trooper and Allen's relatives each took a sip to confirm it was not poisoned, Allen drank the entire jug.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] After 45 minutes, Allen was carried on a stretcher to a waiting ambulance that took her to St.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] John's Hospital in Springfield, where she was assessed to be in good condition.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Inside Allen's house, police found that it was "neat and tidy" aside from windows that had been broken by police over the course of the standoff.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen had been sleeping in her living room, where John had died, and kept her shotgun on a table there.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] She also had two battery-powered radios tuned to WUIS, the NPR station in Springfield, which was coincidentally the only media outlet in the area Gainer had not contacted about the standoff.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Gainer was satisfied with the peaceful end to the standoff, as was Governor Jim Edgar, many Roby residents, and even some Allen sympathizers who had expected a worse conclusion.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen was not charged with any crimes, but she was billed approximately $20,000 for each day that the standoff lasted.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The ISP agreed to pay for her broken windows alongside any damage police had inflicted to her property during the standoff.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Allen was transferred to the custody of the Andrew McFarland Mental Health Center.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] On December 16, after 47 days of hospitalization, she was released back to her home in Roby awaiting a court-ordered psychiatric evaluation to determine if she required further commitment, after doctors declared she did not pose a significant threat.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] As of 2007, she was reported to still be living in her same house in Roby.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The standoff drew national attention as one of the longest standoffs involving a single suspect in history.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] Political controversies over the cost of the operation and involuntary commitment laws ensued.
[src:siege/1997-roby-standoff] The Libertarian Party called for reform of Illinois mental health laws that provide for the hospitalization of people who do not break the law.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Armee*) was a field army of the German Army during World War II.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] It is widely known for its defeat by and subsequent surrender to the Red Army at the Battle of Stalingrad on 2 February 1943.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] It committed war crimes at Babi Yar while under the command of Field Marshal Walther von Reichenau during Operation Barbarossa.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army was reformed in March 1943, and participated in fighting in Ukraine and later Romania, before being almost completely destroyed in the Second Jassy-Kishinev Offensive in August 1944.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Following this it would fight in Hungary, attempting to relieve Budapest, and subsequently retreating into Austria in the Spring of 1945.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] 6th Army surrendered to US Army forces on 9 May 1945.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army was formed on 10 October 1939 with General Walther von Reichenau in command through the redesignation of the 10th Army that had fought during the Invasion of Poland.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] During the invasion of the Low Countries the 6th Army saw active service linking up with paratroopers and destroying fortifications at Eben Emael, Liège, and Namur during the Battle of Belgium.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army was then involved in the breakthrough of the Paris defences on 12 June 1940, before acting as a northern flank for German forces along the Normandy coast during the closing stages of the Battle of France.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Three Infantry Divisions of the 6th Army, based in the Cherbourg Peninsula, were scheduled to land in the area of Lyme Bay during Operation Sea Lion, the planned German invasion of the UK.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army took part in Operation Barbarossa as the spearhead of Army Group South.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Reichenau died in an aircraft accident while being transported to a hospital after a heart attack in January 1942.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] He was succeeded by his former chief of staff, General Friedrich Paulus.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Paulus led the 6th Army to a major victory at the Second Battle of Kharkov during the spring of 1942.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] On 28 June 1942, Army Group South launched Case Blue, the German Army's summer offensive into southern Russia.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The goals of the operation were to secure both the oil fields at Baku, Azerbaijan, and the city of Stalingrad on the river Volga to protect the forces advancing into the Caucasus.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Two months after the beginning of Case Blue, the 6th Army reached the outskirts of Stalingrad on 23 August.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] On the same day, over 1,000 aircraft of the Luftflotte 4 bombed the city, killing many civilians.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Stalingrad was defended by the 62nd Army (Soviet Union) under the command of General Vasily Chuikov.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Despite German air superiority over Stalingrad, and with more artillery pieces than the Red Army, progress was reduced to no more than several meters a day.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Eventually, by mid November, the 62nd Army had been pushed to the banks of the Volga, but the 6th Army was unable to eliminate the remaining Soviet troops.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] On 19 November the Stavka launched Operation Uranus, a major offensive by Soviet forces on the flanks of the German army.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The first pincer attacked far to the west of the Don, with the second thrust beginning a day later attacking far to the south of Stalingrad.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army's flanks were protected by Romanian troops, who were quickly routed, and on 23 November, the pincers met at Kalach-na-Donu, thereby encircling the 6th Army.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] A relief attempt was launched on 12 December by Hermann Hoth's 4th Panzer Army, codenamed Operation Winter Storm.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Despite initial progress, capturing the town of Verkhne-Kumsky and reaching the river Myshkova, the 4th Panzer Army was eventually halted and later forced to withdraw due to the threat posed to its rear by Operation Little Saturn.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Also contributing to Winter Storm's failure was Adolf Hitler's refusal to approve of Operation Thunderclap, a planned breakout attempt by the 6th Army, to occur simultaneously.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th Army surrendered between 31 January and 2 February 1943.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] German casualties were 147,200 killed and wounded and over 91,000 captured, the latter including Field Marshal Paulus, 24 generals and 2,500 officers of lesser rank.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Only 5,000 would survive Soviet internment and return to Germany after the war.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] A new 6th Army was deployed by renaming *Armee-Abteilung Hollidt* on 5 March 1943 under the command of General Karl-Adolf Hollidt.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] This new 6th Army later fought in Ukraine and Romania as part of Army Group South until transferred to Army Group A (later renamed to Army Group South Ukraine).
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] In May 1944, the 6th Army became part of Army Group Dumitrescu, commanded by the Romanian general Petre Dumitrescu.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The Army Group also included the Romanian 3rd Army.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] This instance marked the first time in the war when German commanders came under the actual (instead of nominal) command of their foreign allies.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] This came one month after Dumitrescu became the 5th non-German recipient of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves (4 April 1944).
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The 6th army was encircled and almost entirely destroyed during the Second Jassy–Kishinev Offensive carried out by the Soviets.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] In October 1944, under the command of General Maximilian Fretter-Pico, the 6th Army encircled and destroyed three Soviet corps of Mobile Group Pliyev under the command of Issa Pliyev in the Battle of Debrecen.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] During this time, the 6th Army had the Hungarian Second Army placed under its command, and it was known as "Army Group Fretter-Pico" (*Armeegruppe Fretter-Pico*).
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Command passed to General Hermann Balck on 23 December 1944.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] In December 1944, one of the 6th Army's subordinate units, the IX SS Mountain Corps, was encircled in Budapest.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] IV SS Panzer Corps was transferred to the 6th Army's command and a series of relief attempts, codenamed Operation Konrad, was launched during the 46-day-long Siege of Budapest.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] After the failure of Konrad III, the 6th Army was made part of "Army Group Balck" (*Armeegruppe Balck*).
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] This army group fell back to the area near Lake Balaton.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Several units, including the III Panzer Corps, took part in Operation Spring Awakening, while the rest of the Sixth Army provided defence for the left flank of the offensive, in the region west of Székesfehérvár.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] After the failure of the offensive, the army held the line until the Soviet Vienna Offensive on 16 March 1945.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] This offensive tore a gap in the 6th Army between the IV SS Panzer Corps and the 3rd Hungarian Army (subordinated to Balck's command), shattering the formation.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] By the end of March 1945, the 6th Army was retreating towards Vienna.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Soon after the beginning of Operation Barbarossa, the Sixth Army's surgeon, the staff doctor Gerhart Panning, learned about captured Russian expanding bullets by using Jewish POWs.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] To determine the effects of this type of ammunition on German soldiers, he decided to test them on other human beings after asking SD member and *SS-Standartenführer* Paul Blobel for some "guinea pigs" (Jewish POWs).
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] In July 1941 while conducting operations in Right-bank Ukraine, the Sixth Army bloodlessly captured the Ukrainian town of Bila Tserkva.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Immediately after the town's capitulation, Sixth Army police units separated the Jewish population of the town into a ghetto and required that they wear the Star of David as identification.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Two weeks after the occupation, members of *Einsatzgruppen* marched the Jews out of the town, 800 men and women in all, to be shot.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The Sixth Army provided logistical support for this massacre, providing drivers, guards, weapons and ammunition.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Afterwards ninety children aged twelve and under were left, their parents having been killed the night before.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Groscurth himself sought out the district commander and insisted that the execution must be stopped.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Sixth Army headquarters was faced with a decision on what to do with the children left behind now that their parents had been murdered.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The division commander passed the decision up to Walter von Reichenau, then commander of the Sixth Army, who personally authorized the massacre.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] All the children were murdered by Sixth Army regulars.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Groscurth, appalled by the murders, wrote to his wife that "We cannot and should not be allowed to win this war".
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The army's commander, Walther von Reichenau, a committed, fanatical Nazi, had this to say about the expected conduct of soldiers under his command.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Immediately after this order was issued, Sixth Army records show a dramatic increase in shootings, rapes and massacres committed by Sixth Army constituent units.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] The Sixth Army confiscated large quantities of food to be used by its troops, creating acute food shortages in Ukraine.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] By January 1942, around one-third of the Kharkov's 300,000 remaining inhabitants suffered from starvation.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Many would die in the cold winter months.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Civilians survived the famine by making stews out of boiled leather and sawdust, and making omelets out of coagulated blood.
[src:siege/6th-army-wehrmacht] Survivors bitterly remembered these "meals" for the rest of their lives.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:siege/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] An **aerial bomb** is a type of explosive or incendiary weapon intended to travel through the air on a predictable trajectory.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Engineers usually develop such bombs to be dropped from an aircraft.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] The use of aerial bombs is termed **aerial bombing**.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Aerial bombs include a vast range and complexity of designs.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] These include unguided gravity bombs, guided bombs, bombs hand-tossed from a vehicle, bombs needing a large specially-built delivery-vehicle, bombs integrated with the vehicle itself (such as a glide bomb), instant-detonation bombs, or delay-action bombs.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] As with other types of explosive weapons, aerial bombs aim to kill and injure people or to destroy materiel through the projection of one or more of blast, fragmentation, radiation or fire outwards from the point of detonation.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] The first bombs delivered to their targets by air were single bombs carried on unmanned hot air balloons, launched by the Austrians against Venice in 1849 during the First Italian War of Independence.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] The first bombs dropped from a heavier-than-air aircraft were grenades or grenade-like devices.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Historically, the first use was by Giulio Gavotti on 1 November 1911, during the Italo-Turkish War.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] In 1912, during the First Balkan War, Bulgarian Air Force pilot Hristo Toprakchiev suggested the use of aircraft to drop "bombs" (called grenades in the Bulgarian army at this time) on Turkish positions.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Captain Simeon Petrov developed the idea and created several prototypes by adapting different types of grenades and increasing their payload.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] On 16 October 1912, observer Prodan Tarakchiev dropped two of those bombs on the Turkish railway station of Karaağaç (near the besieged Edirne) from an Albatros F.2 aircraft piloted by Radul Milkov, for the first time in this campaign.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] During the Mexican Revolution, US inventor Lester P.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Barlow convinced General Pancho Villa of the insurgent Villista forces to purchase a plane from which bombs were dropped on trains carrying on Mexican Federal troops.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Although the bombs were weak, they launched Barlow's career as an explosives inventor.
[src:siege/aerial-bomb] Aerial bombing saw widespread use during World War Two.
